Elemental analyses (Table S1) of our samples (Fig. 6
                        ) were done with energy dispersive X-ray spectroscopy (EDS). EDS analyses of CQDs and N-CQDs, presented in Fig. 6A and B reveal the presence of C and O atom in both of them. The sources of oxygen in both of them are citric acid (C6H8O7) and ascorbic acid (C6H8O6) of the lemon juice [40,43,46]. Presence of N (12.6 %) in the EDS spectrum of N-CQDs confirms its successful doping with EDTA. The percent oxygen content in CQDs and N-CQDs is 38.3 and 42.7 %, respectively. Thus, we can conclude that the concentration of oxygenated groups is higher in N-CQDs. N-CQDs possessing both oxygenated and nitrogenated groups can induce more pseudocapacitance than CQDs [10,12–14,38–41], and hence its C
                        sp is anticipated to be higher than that of CQDs.
